description: From Late Latin typicalis, from Latin typicus (“typical”), from Ancient Greek τυπικός (tupikós, “of or pertaining to a type, conformable, typical”), from τύπος (túpos, “mark, impression, type”), equivalent to typic +‎ -al and type +‎ -ical.

adjectives.description: typical (comparative more typical, superlative most typical)

entries.meaning: Capturing the overall sense of a thing.
Characteristically representing something by form, group, idea or type.
(taxonomy) Of a lower taxon, containing the type of the higher taxon.
Anything that is typical, normal, or standard.
examples: Antipsychotic drugs can be divided into typicals and atypicals.
Among the moths, typicals were more common than melanics.
